Conclusion¶

For every dataframe date columns was changed format from 'object' to 'datetime' to save memory space. The 'device' column type in visits_df was changed to category for the same reason. No duplicated rows were found in any dataframe. 51 rows with zero revenue value were dropped from orders dataframe. The data beyond 365 days scope was removed from orders dataframe.

Most of the users return the same day or never return at all. For the rest of the users it is better to create retention groups:
Retention 0d, 1d, 3d, 7d, 14d, 30d, 3m, 6m, 1y
0d retention includes both who returned the same day and never returned at all.

In [41]:
lifetime_list = ['0 days', '1 day', '3 days', '7 days', '14 days', '30 days', '90 days', '180 days', '>180 days']
def assign_lifetime_group(days):
    
    try:
        if days == 0:
            return 0
        elif days == 1:
            return 1
        elif ((days > 1) and (days <= 3)):
            return 3
        elif ((days > 3) and (days <= 7)):
            return 7
        elif ((days > 7) and (days <= 14)):
            return 14
        elif ((days > 14) and (days <= 30)):
            return 30
        elif ((days > 30) and (days <= 90)):
            return 90
        elif ((days > 90) and (days <= 180)):
            return 180
        elif days > 180:
            return 360
    except:
        return numpy.nan
    
visits_df['cohort_lifetime'] = visits_df.apply(lambda x: assign_lifetime_group(x['ret_total']), axis=1)
In [42]:
visits_df['cohort_lifetime'] = visits_df['cohort_lifetime'].fillna(0)
vdf = visits_df.drop_duplicates('uid')
cohorts = vdf.groupby(['first_visit','cohort_lifetime']).agg({'uid':'nunique'}).reset_index()

retention_pivot = cohorts.pivot_table(index='first_visit',columns='cohort_lifetime',values='retention',aggfunc='sum')

sns.set(style='white')
plt.figure(figsize=(23, 18))
plt.title('Cohorts: User Retention')
sns.heatmap(retention_pivot, annot=True, fmt='.1%', linewidths=1, xticklabels=lifetime_list, linecolor='gray');

As we see from the heatmap above, most of the users use the service only once and hardly return afterwards. If they do, it happens more than 90 days after initial use.

Conclusion:¶

907 people use the service daily, 5621 weekly, 23228 monthly in average. The best season is October-March, when service visits spike. Median session time is 5 minutes. People start to return to use the service mostly after a period of 90 days (the best numbers are for September cohort, probably most of which are students), which makes sense due to specifics of the service - people usually do not attend concerts and events every week, rather once in a couple of month, hence the retention rates.

On the heatmap above we see that most purchases occure in cohorts with 0 month age - people buy once after first visit and do not return. However there is one clear outlier for the September cohort at 3 month age - just befoore the holidays season. I assume most of the cohort are students, and they wish to have fun at some holiday events before the exam period started.

Conclusion:¶

Most of the people make their first purchase the same day they first visit the servise. This rate rises in October and stays high until the end of the year holidays.
The amount of orders stays above 5000 per month from October to March, with a little drop in January.
The average purchse size remains roughly the same throughout the year - around 5.
After initial purchase (which is around 2 rub per user), LTV continue to grow slowly due to small retention, and may reach around 5 rub for 12 month old cohort, with some exception (September cohort).

Conclusion¶

330000 rub was the marketing cost for 12 months, almost half of those money wen on source #3. This investment did not payed off, the revenue from this channel is very low relative to investments - almost 55000. But it is the second biggest revenue among the channels.

Step 3. An overall conclusion.¶

As seen on the chart above, there are some of the marketing channesl were a failure, and it would be a good idea to reallocate those investments to other sources.

  • Source #1. That's an example of a great investment, it brought a thirth more money that've been invested.
  • Source #2 is also profitable, but not like #1.
  • Source #3 was an unfortunate investment. It had the highest infusion, but returned only a small part of investments. Let's check in terms of visits:
In [81]:
visits_df.drop_duplicates('uid').groupby('source_id')['uid'].nunique().plot(kind='bar', title='Visits attracted per marketing source')
Out[81]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7fe60dcc4dd0>
  • In terms of visits channel #3 is the second most succesful. But all those visits brought a very small amount of revenue. I recommend to cut the marketing expenses on this channel significantly.
  • Source #4 marketing costs were slightly bigger than a revenue generated by this channel, but this channel brought the best visits quantity, so in terms of brand recognition this channel is a great success. We should possibly invest more in this channel.
  • Source #5 brought slightly more money than was invested and is on third place in visitors attracted, definetly a good source to invest more.
  • Sources #9 and #10 are the smallest investments. #9 slightly paid off, #10 did not. They both attracted a similar amount of users, so probably #9 should be infused a little bit more.
